\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator finds that the programme meets the minimum requirements in terms of all the criteria that are relevant for public institutions and recommended that the programme be accredited with conditions. \line \line The proposed Master of Laws in The Law of Mineral and Petroleum Extraction and Use\'2C is an endeavour with the Research Chair\'3A Mineral Law in Africa \'28MLiA\'29. The proposed programme is consonant with the mission and vision and is clearly aligned to its Strategic Plan. The degree addresses both \'E2\'80\'98black letter law\'E2\'80\'99 and the underlying theory and socio-political context. Provision is made for guest lecturers to present a wide range of inter-disciplinary perspectives and practical insight into the mining-society-community-matrix. It is envisaged that students from other African jurisdictions will gain from the programme. The proposed Master\'E2\'80\'99s is a unique new postgraduate programme\'2C focused on a key driver of the South African economy\'2C and an important developmental \'28and strategic\'29 asset of the African continent. \line \line The programme consists of three compulsory modules of 30 credits \'28NQF Level 9\'29 each. A further three compulsory modules at NQF level 9 of 15 credits contains the research tasks corresponding to the first three modules. Students may then choose one of three optional modules at NQF level 9\'2C and then another three corresponding research tasks comprising of 15 credits. For both the compulsory and the elective modules\'2C students will complete a main\'2Fprimary coursework module \'2830 credits each\'29 and a corresponding research task \'2815 credits each\'29. Research is thus allocated a total of 90 credits. Each of the research tasks require students to conduct research\'2C to analyse and to solve a practical problem. The total credit count for this programme is 180 credits.  \line \line Applicants must be graduates of an NQF level 8 law degree\'2C or equivalent. An aggregate of 65\'25 for LLB graduates is usually required\'2C however relevant work experience may also be taken into account. Provision is made for access via RPL. Target enrolments are 10 to 15 students in the first year\'2C for 2021\'2C another 15 to 20 students will be enrolled by 2022. \line \line The staff complement is in place for the programme\'2C and is headed by the MLiA\'2C a well-respected academic locally and abroad. The programme will also reply on an extended network of guest lecturers. \line \line The general Teaching and Learning Strategy will be \'E2\'80\'9Cas practical and contextual as possible\'E2\'80\'9D. Contact time will take the form of a lecture\'2C tutorial or seminar requiring pre-class reading and preparation. Provision will be made for student monitoring and personal interventions for the identified at-risk students.\line \line In terms of assessment\'2C students will be assessed on their ability to apply the knowledge acquired\'2C to conduct research\'2C to apply the laws and principles to practical scenarios\'2C and to evaluate critically the theory and policies underpinning the laws relating to mineral and petroleum extraction and use. Students will be taught to formulate legal arguments and resolve legal disputes as well as the ability to account for non-legal considerations. \line \line The evaluator notes that given that the proposed Master\'E2\'80\'99s does not entail a dissertation as part of the programme\'2C it is not clear that the minimum standards of Criterion 9 apply. Please see the Directorate discussion in this respect\'2C below.  \line \line The evaluator recommends accreditation with the conditions that information for Criteria 6\'2C 7\'2C and 8 should be provided. \line However\'2C 7 and 8 are not required from a public provider\'2C and as far as assessment \'28Criterion 6\'29 is concerned\'2C the Institution has responded\'2C appropriately\'2C in the section on postgraduate study \'28Criterion 9\'29. The Directorate is of the view that the evaluator could have reached the conclusion below with a more flexible reading of the two sections together. The latter in particular sets out clearly why there are differences between the standard assessment of a research \'2F coursework master\'E2\'80\'99s and this one. It is the view of the Directorate that the approach is adequate and if the research complies with the requirements for research other than a dissertation \'28as set out in the HEQSF\'29 then the assessment proposed clearly meets these needs. Secondly\'2C and in a related point\'2C external examination of each piece of research is provided for\'2C and moderation of all the other modules is conducted as per the policy for a standard Master\'E2\'80\'99s degree. \line \line The Directorate is of the view that the programme should be accredited without conditions.\cell \pard 

